3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates MKR/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices. The exchange's zero maker fee policy allows arbitrageurs to enter and exit positions without paying maker fees, improving profitability compared to traditional 0.02% maker fee structures. Funding payments are automatically debited or credited to trader accounts, with rates typically ranging from -0.375% to +0.375% per funding period."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","MKR","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MKR's role as MakerDAO's governance token creates distinct funding rate patterns driven by DeFi protocol developments and governance proposals. The token's mid-tier volume on MEXC provides sufficient liquidity for moderate-sized arbitrage positions while maintaining meaningful rate spreads. MKR's correlation with broader DeFi sentiment often leads to sustained funding rate imbalances during protocol upgrades or market stress."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MKR/USDT funding rates on MEXC exhibit cyclical patterns tied to MakerDAO governance cycles and DeFi market sentiment. During major protocol upgrades or DAI stability issues, funding rates often turn negative as traders short MKR, creating opportunities for long arbitrage positions. The token's lower trading frequency compared to major assets results in more persistent funding rate imbalances. Weekly analysis shows funding rates averaging -0.05% during bear markets and +0.12% during DeFi bull runs."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Execution"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fees enable profitable arbitrage on smaller funding rate spreads that would be unprofitable on fee-charging exchanges. The 8-hour funding cycle provides multiple daily opportunities to capture rate premiums, particularly effective during DeFi governance events when spot-perp premiums persist. Cross-exchange arbitrage between MEXC and Binance or OKX often yields 0.02-0.08% profit per cycle due to MEXC's aggressive pricing. Position sizing should account for MKR's mid-tier liquidity, with optimal trade sizes typically under $50,000 to avoid significant slippage."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MKR's governance token nature introduces unique risks including proposal-driven volatility and potential protocol changes affecting token utility. MEXC's reported volume accuracy concerns require careful order book analysis before executing large positions. The exchange's regulatory uncertainties could impact withdrawal processes during market stress periods. Implement stop-losses at 2-3% to manage directional risk, and monitor MakerDAO governance proposals that could trigger sudden price movements exceeding typical funding rate gains."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does MEXC's zero maker fee affect MKR funding rate arbitrage profitability?","answer":"MEXC's zero maker fees improve arbitrage profitability by eliminating the typical 0.02% entry cost, allowing profitable trades on smaller funding rate spreads. This fee advantage makes MKR arbitrage viable even with funding rates as low as 0.005% per cycle."},{"question":"What funding rate thresholds make MKR arbitrage profitable on MEXC?","answer":"With zero maker fees, MKR arbitrage becomes profitable at funding rates above 0.01% per cycle to cover taker fees and slippage. Optimal opportunities typically occur when rates exceed 0.03% per 8-hour period, providing meaningful returns after transaction costs."},{"question":"How does MakerDAO governance affect MKR funding rates?","answer":"Governance proposals and protocol changes often create directional bias in MKR markets, leading to sustained funding rate imbalances. Major updates like collateral additions or stability fee changes can maintain negative or positive funding for several cycles, creating extended arbitrage opportunities."},{"question":"What are the liquidity constraints for MKR arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"MEXC's MKR order books typically support positions up to $30,000-50,000 without significant slippage. Larger positions may require staged execution across multiple funding periods to avoid market impact that could negate arbitrage profits."}]}]
